<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-10-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-10-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="17" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d17">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 711.0012/656</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of the Secretary of State</hi>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-10-05">
                                <hi rend="italic">October 5, 1914</hi>.</date>
                        </dateline>
                        <p>German Ambassador called in response to my suggestion that he exert his
                            influence in behalf of the negotiation of a treaty similar to those
                            signed with the twenty-seven other countries. Gave him copies of the
                            British, French, Russian, and Netherlands treaties. He expressed great
                            interest in the subject and said he would send them to Berlin and do
                            what he could to induce his Government to join in a similar treaty.</p>
                    </div>
